g.text: Species distribution models (SDMs) are spatial representations of species presence probability or abundance.
They are created using responses to environmental predictor variables, spatial relationships such as convex hulls or
interpolation, or a combination of the two. SDMs are easily projected across landscapes, and can therefore be help-
ful in circumstances where acquiring occurrence data on the distribution of species is not achievable, or when the
ecological variables related to the distribution of the species have changed (reviewed by Guisan and Thuiller 2005
